04939nam a22006375i 9780520975521DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209755217 a10.1525/97805209755212doi  a(DE-B1597)551569  a(OCoLC)1124788104  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML270.8.P2 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a780.92/2472231 aMoricz, Klara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Stravinsky's Orbit :bResponses to Modernism in Russian Paris /cKlara Moricz. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (310 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in 20th-Century Music ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- t1. Double Narratives or Dukelsky’s The End of St. Petersburg -- t2. Soviet “méchanique” or the Bolshevik Temptation -- t3. Neoclassicism à la russe 1 or Reclaiming the Eighteenth Century in Nabokov’s Ode -- t4. Neoclassicism à la russe 2 or Stravinsky’s Version of Similia similibus curentur -- t5. 1937 or Pushkin Divided -- t6. A Feast in Time of Plague -- t7. Epilogue or Firebird to Phoenix -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Bolsheviks’ 1917 political coup caused a seismic disruption in Russian culture. Carried by the first wave of emigrants, Russian culture migrated West, transforming itself as it interacted with the new cultural environment and clashed with exported Soviet trends. In this book, Klára Móricz explores the transnational emigrant space of Russian composers Igor Stravinsky, Vladimir Dukelsky, Sergey Prokofiev, Nicolas Nabokov, and Arthur Lourié in interwar Paris. Their music reflected the conflict between a modernist narrative demanding innovation and a narrative of exile wedded to the preservation of prerevolutionary Russian culture. The emigrants’ and the Bolsheviks’ contrasting visions of Russia and its past collided frequently in the French capital, where the Soviets displayed their political and artistic products. Russian composers in Paris also had to reckon with Stravinsky’s disproportionate influence: if they succumbed to fashions dictated by their famous compatriot, they risked becoming epigones; if they kept to their old ways, they quickly became irrelevant. Although Stravinsky’s neoclassicism provided a seemingly neutral middle ground between innovation and nostalgia, it was also marked by the exilic experience. Móricz offers this unexplored context for Stravinsky’s neoclassicism, shedding new light on this infinitely elusive term.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComposerszSoviet Union. 0aExpatriate composerszFrancezParis. 0aMusiczFrancezParisy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520975521?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975521423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520975521/original  a978-3-11-069041-5  Universit